Docker Networking:
==>Docker is an OS level virtualization software platform that help users to develop, deply, manage and run applications in the docker contianer with all their library dependencies.
==>Docker Networking enables users to link a docker container to as many networks as required. Docker networks are used to provide complete isolation for docker container. One can add containers to more than one network. Containers netwroking refers to the ability for containers to connect and communicate each other, or to non-docker work loads.
Publishing ports:-
By default when you create a container or run a container, the container doesnt expose any of its ports to outside world. Use --publish or -p option to make a port available to services outside of docker. This creates a firewall rule in a host, mapping a container port to host to the outside world.
==>Each container connected to a private virtual netowrk called "Bridge" 
==>Each virtual network routes thorugh NAT firewall on host ip.
==>All containers on a virtual network can talk to each other without -p option.
==>Best practice is to create a new virtual network for each applicaton.
==>The default networks work well in many cases, but easy to swap out parts to customise it. 
==>You can make new virtual network works, can attach containers to more than one network or none.
==>You can skip virtual networks and use HostIP (--net=host).
==>You can use different docker network drivers to gain new abilities. The underlying software that provide core networking functionality is called 'Drivers'. Docker networking subsystem is pluggable using drivers.
==>The default network driver is "Bridge"
   1.Bridge: This is default network driver, used to communicate one container with another within same host.
   2.Host: Host drivers removes network isolation between container and docker hosts and use host netorking directly.
   3.Overlay: Overlay network drivers creates a distributed network among multiple docker daemon hosts (used in cluster).
   4.IPVLAN:
   5.MACVLAN
   6.None: refers to isolate container from host as well s other containers.
