Docker Networks default security:-
1.Create your applications in a such a way frontend/backend exists on the same docker network
2.Their inter communication never leaves host, hence it is secured
3.All externally exposed ports closed by default. You must manually expose via -p or --publish option, which is better default security.
4.Using Static IPs for container communication is an anti-pattern. You need to avoid it.
5.Containers constantly launching, removing, moving, expanding, shrinking cause to no longer rely on ip address for their inter communication. The solution for htis is DNS naming.
6.Docker uses the container names as equivalent of a hostname and uses hostname to talk to each other.
7.Docker daemon has a built-in DNS server that contianers use by default.
8.Docker defaults the hostname to the containers name, but you can also set aliases.
9.Please note taht the default bridge network has one disadvantage, where as it does not have DNS server built-in by default.

