Docker Volumes:
-->Containers are usually immuntable and ephemeral
-->Immunatale infrastructure:
   Only re-deply containers, they never change
-->Persistent Storage: 2 ways; volumes and bind mounts
Volumes: Make a special location outside of the containers
Bind Mounts: Link container path to host path

                             ..............................
                             :            HOST            :
			     :  ........................  :
		             :  .       Container      :  :
                             :  : /var/lib/myql/data   :--:---->Virtual Filesystem  
                             :  :......................:  :     Container Directory
			     :                            :
                             :  ........................  :
                             :  :   /home/mount/data   :--:-----> Host file system 
			     :  ........................  :       (Physical Filesystem)
                             :                            :
                             :............................:
-->The Data in the virtual filesystem is removed when container is restarted/removed and when started it, it starts from fresh state
-->The solution to make the data persistent that the application is making with docker volumes.
-->Folder in the physical host file system is mounted into the virtual filesystem of docker. When container writes to filesystem, it gets replicated/automatically written in host filesystem directory. In this case, when container restarted, it gets the data from host filesystem.
-->Docker volumes are used for data persistence in the container. Example, databases, stateful applications etc.,you would want to use docker volumes.
-->Docker volumes are preferred mechanism for persistent data. Docker volume is a storae where data remains when container is turned off, such as databases, other stateful applications.
1.Host Volumes:
--> Exists on the docker host filesystem
--> Access within the container
-->This type of volumes are ideal for simple projects
   ex:- docker run -v /path/to/host:/path/in/Container
                where -v: volume
2.Anonymous Volumes:
-->Docker handles storage location(host)
-->Difficult to refer to the multiple containers
-->Anonymous docker volumes are named by docker, the name is random hash code. 
-->Docker creates a directory under "/var/lib/docker/volumes/Volume_name/_data
3.Named Volumes:
-->Named volumes are like anonymous volumes
-->Docker manages location of volume
-->Difference is, we name the volume.

Commands:-
docker volume create : Creates anonymous volume in /var/lib/docker/volumes/XXXHashCodeXXX/_data
docker volume create vol_name : Create a volume /var/lib/docker/volumes/vol_name/_data
docker volume ls  : list the existing volumes
docker volume rm vol_name : removes the volume
docker volume prune : removes anonymous volumes that are not associated with any container
docker volume inspect volume_name
Examples:
a)docker container run --volume /mydata -dit --name mydata_web -p 80:80 nginx /bin/bash -->  anonymous volume
b)docker container run --volume mydatavol:/mydata -dit --name mydata_web -p 80:80 nginx /bin/bash --> named volume
c)sudo mkdir /myWorks
  docker container run --volume /myWorks:/mydata -dit --name mydata_web -p 80:80 nginx /bin/bash -->binded volume
  The above type of volumes you should use in production
Note: You dont have any way to add volume in running containers.
